---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import LayerSection from '../components/LayerSection.astro';
import { networkLayers } from '../data/networkLayers.js';
import Encapsulation from '../components/Encapsulation.svelte';
import Packets from '../components/Packets.svelte';
import Tcp from '../components/Tcp.svelte';
import Routing from '../components/Routing.svelte';
import Dns from '../components/Dns.svelte';
import Sockets from '../components/Sockets.svelte';
import Http from '../components/Http.svelte';
import Why from '../components/Why.astro';
import Takeaway from '../components/Takeaway.astro';
import Advanced from '../components/Advanced.astro';
import Quiz from '../components/Quiz.svelte';
import PrevNext from '../components/PrevNext.astro';
import SeeAlso from '../components/SeeAlso.astro';
const L = Object.fromEntries(networkLayers.map((l) => [l.id, l]));
const title = 'THE STACK — the network, deep';
const description = 'A deep dive into the network stack: signals on the wire, encapsulation, IP routing and TTL, TCP reliability, and DNS — how bytes leave one machine and arrive at another.';
---
<Base {title} {description} layers={networkLayers}>
  <div slot="hero">
    <div class="kicker">A deep dive into layer 16</div>
    <h1 class="title">THE <em>NETWORK</em><br />STACK</h1>
    <p class="lede">In the main stack, "the network" is one rung. Pull it apart and it's a whole ladder of its own — each layer wrapping the one above, just to get a few bytes across the world and back.</p>
    <div class="hero-meta"><a class="back-link" href="/">← back to the full stack</a> · signals → encapsulation → routing → reliability → congestion → DNS → sockets → HTTP</div>
  </div>

  <LayerSection {...L.N0}>
    <p class="prose">A wire can't send a "1" — only a <b>signal</b>: a voltage on copper, a pulse of light in fiber, a modulated radio wave. Both ends agree how to read it back as bits, and how fast (<span class="hl">bandwidth</span>) with how much delay (<span class="hl">latency</span>).</p>
    <Takeaway>Networking starts where layer 00 left off: bits encoded as a physical signal — now travelling between buildings instead of between gates.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p><b>Bandwidth and latency are independent.</b> Bandwidth is how many bits per second the link carries; latency is how long one bit takes to arrive — and fibre signals already travel near light speed, so latency is bounded by distance, not by buying a "faster" connection. A satellite link can have huge bandwidth yet terrible latency.</p>
      <p>Their product, the <b>bandwidth-delay product</b>, is how many bits are "in flight" in the pipe at once — the amount a sender must keep unacknowledged to fill it. A fat, long link needs a large in-flight window, which is exactly why transport-layer window sizing (next layers up) matters so much over high-latency paths.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="Two machines aren't wired into the same circuit, so a bit can't just be a shared voltage — it has to survive a long, noisy, shared medium."
      idea="Encode bits as signals tuned to the medium (copper, fiber, radio) with agreed timing, then let higher layers worry about meaning."
      tradeoff="Distance and sharing cost you: signals attenuate, collide, and arrive late — bandwidth and latency become first-class constraints."
      next="Once a link can carry bits between neighbours, data needs a wrapper that says who it's for."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.N1}>
    <p class="prose">Data leaves wrapped like a parcel inside a parcel: your bytes get a transport header (ports), then an IP header (addresses), then a link frame (MAC + checksum). Each layer only reads its own wrapper.</p>
    <Encapsulation client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Each layer adds just enough header to do its job and trusts the layer below to deliver the rest — that's encapsulation.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>Each link caps how big a frame it will carry — its <b>MTU</b> (typically 1500 bytes on Ethernet). A packet larger than a link's MTU must be <b>fragmented</b> into pieces and reassembled, which is costly and fragile: lose one fragment and the whole packet is gone. IPv6 forbids in-network fragmentation entirely, pushing the job to the sender.</p>
      <p>So senders run <b>Path MTU Discovery</b>: mark packets "don't fragment" and let any too-small hop reply with an <code>ICMP</code> "too big" message carrying the limit, then shrink to fit. When firewalls wrongly block that ICMP, you get a <b>PMTUD black hole</b> — small requests work, large transfers mysteriously hang.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="A bare payload has no idea where it's going, which program should receive it, or whether it arrived intact."
      idea="Wrap it in nested headers — transport, network, link — each carrying exactly the context that layer needs, added on the way down and stripped on the way up."
      tradeoff="Every header is overhead: a tiny request rides inside far more bytes, the price of routing, addressing, and integrity."
      next="The IP header is what lets routers move the parcel across the world."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.N2}>
    <p class="prose">No single wire reaches the destination. The packet <b>hops</b> from router to router; each one reads the destination IP, consults its routing table, and forwards toward it. A <span class="hl">TTL</span> counts down so a misrouted packet can't circle forever.</p>
    <Routing client:visible />
    <Takeaway>IP is best-effort delivery by hops: every router makes a local "which way is closer?" decision, and TTL bounds the journey.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>IPv4 has too few addresses for every device, so home and office networks hide behind <b>NAT</b>: the gateway rewrites the private source IP and port of outgoing packets to its own single public IP, and keeps a translation table to send replies back to the right inside host. Many devices share one public address this way.</p>
      <p>NAT works because a flow is identified by its full <b>4-tuple</b> (source IP:port ↔ destination IP:port), so the gateway can multiplex many inside hosts onto one address by juggling ports. The cost is that unsolicited inbound connections have no table entry and are dropped — which is why peer-to-peer apps need <b>hole punching</b> or relays to connect.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="The destination could be anywhere on Earth, across networks owned by strangers — there's no direct wire and no global map."
      idea="Give every machine an IP address and let each router forward a packet one hop closer using its own routing table. No router knows the whole path."
      tradeoff="Best-effort means packets can be dropped, delayed, duplicated, or reordered, and routing loops are only stopped by the TTL counting down to zero."
      next="If IP can lose packets, something above it has to make delivery reliable."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.N3}>
    <p class="prose">IP makes no promises, so TCP layers reliability on top: it numbers every packet, the receiver acknowledges what arrived, and anything missing is <b>retransmitted</b> and reassembled in order.</p>
    <Packets client:visible />
    <Takeaway>TCP turns lossy, out-of-order packets into a clean ordered byte-stream — at the cost of acks, buffering, and waiting for stragglers.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>TCP's strict ordering causes <b>head-of-line blocking</b>: if one segment is lost, every byte that arrived <i>after</i> it must wait in the buffer until the gap is retransmitted, even data the application could already use. Running many independent streams over one TCP connection (as HTTP/2 does) makes this worse — one lost packet stalls <i>all</i> the streams sharing that connection.</p>
      <p>That's a core reason <b>QUIC</b> (the basis of HTTP/3) was built on <b>UDP</b> instead: it implements its own per-stream reliability, so a loss on one stream doesn't block the others. Apps that prefer freshness over completeness — live video, games — skip TCP entirely and use UDP so a lost packet is simply dropped rather than holding everything up.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="Applications want an ordered, gap-free stream of bytes, but the layer beneath drops and reorders packets freely."
      idea="Number each segment, acknowledge what arrives, retransmit what doesn't, and reassemble in order before handing the stream up."
      tradeoff="Reliability adds round-trips, buffering, and head-of-line blocking — which is exactly why some apps choose bare UDP instead."
      next="Reliability assumes a connection already exists and that you know how fast to send — but both have to be established first."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.N4}>
    <p class="prose">Before a byte of data flows, TCP <b>opens</b> the connection with a three-way handshake (<code>SYN</code> → <code>SYN-ACK</code> → <code>ACK</code>). Then it faces a question the network never answers directly: how fast can I send? It <b>probes</b> — the congestion window (<span class="hl">cwnd</span>) doubles each round-trip in <i>slow start</i>, then creeps up <b>+1</b> per round-trip; a lost packet caught early (by duplicate acks → <i>fast retransmit</i>) <b>halves</b> it, while a full <b>timeout</b> is treated as worse — cwnd drops all the way back to 1 and slow-starts again. That additive-increase / multiplicative-decrease rhythm is TCP's sawtooth.</p>
    <Tcp client:visible />
    <Takeaway>TCP opens with a handshake, then finds a safe sending rate by itself: ramp up until loss, back off hard, repeat — sharing the link fairly without ever being told its capacity.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>TCP infers loss two ways, and treats them very differently. <b>Three duplicate ACKs</b> (the receiver re-acking the last in-order byte while later packets keep arriving) signal an <i>isolated</i> drop: the sender does a <b>fast retransmit</b>, roughly <b>halves</b> cwnd, and stays in congestion avoidance. An <b>RTO timeout</b> — no ACKs at all — implies a far worse outage: cwnd collapses to <b>1</b> and the connection restarts in <i>slow start</i>.</p>
      <p>The congestion-control algorithm decides the recovery curve. Classic <b>Reno</b> is the additive-increase / multiplicative-decrease sawtooth; <b>CUBIC</b> (Linux default) grows by a cubic function of time since the last loss to fill big "fat-long" pipes faster; and <b>BBR</b> ignores loss as the signal entirely, instead modelling the path's bandwidth and round-trip time to pace just below the point of building queues.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="Two ends must agree to talk before sending, and neither knows how much the path in between can carry — push too hard and you cause the very congestion that drops your packets."
      idea="Open with a three-way handshake, then treat loss as the signal: grow the congestion window while acks arrive, and cut it sharply the moment one goes missing."
      tradeoff="Using loss as the only feedback means TCP repeatedly overshoots and backs off (the sawtooth), and a single lost packet can throttle a fast link — which is why modern variants probe with delay and pacing instead."
      next="A connection that's open and paced still needs the destination's address — and humans type names, not numbers."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.N5}>
    <p class="prose">You typed a name, but routing needs a number. DNS is the phone book: a resolver walks the name hierarchy — root, then the <code>.dev</code> top-level domain, then the domain's own authoritative server — until something answers with an IP.</p>
    <Dns client:visible />
    <Takeaway>DNS turns a human name into an IP by asking down a hierarchy and caching the answer — the same "names are an agreement" idea as encoding.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>Classic DNS rides on <b>UDP</b> and is unauthenticated, which makes <b>cache poisoning</b> possible: an attacker who guesses the query's 16-bit transaction ID and source port can race a forged reply into a resolver's cache, where it poisons every later lookup until the <b>TTL</b> expires. Source-port randomization raised the bar; <b>DNSSEC</b> closes it properly by signing records so a resolver can verify authenticity.</p>
      <p>The query itself is also visible in plaintext, leaking which sites you visit even over an HTTPS connection. <b>DNS over HTTPS / TLS</b> (DoH/DoT) encrypts the lookup, and that <code>TTL</code> on every record is the dial that trades propagation speed (low TTL) against load and resilience (high TTL).</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="People remember names, but every layer below this one only routes to numeric IP addresses."
      idea="Run a distributed, hierarchical directory: ask a root server who handles the suffix, follow referrals down to the authoritative server, and cache the result."
      tradeoff="Caching makes it fast but means changes take time to propagate, and the whole system is a high-value target for spoofing and outages."
      next="Now you have the server's IP. But the server runs many things — which one gets your bytes?"
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.N6}>
    <p class="prose">An IP gets you to the machine; a <b>port</b> gets you to the program on it. A <span class="hl">socket</span> is that endpoint — an IP plus a port. A web server listens on one port (443), yet serves thousands of clients at once: the OS tells the connections apart by the full <b>4-tuple</b> (your ip:port ↔ the server's ip:port) and demuxes each arriving packet to the right one.</p>
    <Sockets client:visible />
    <Takeaway>A socket is an ip:port endpoint; a connection is identified by all four (both ends), so one listening port can hold thousands of simultaneous connections apart.</Takeaway>
    <SeeAlso slug="os" note="the OS owns these sockets and the table that demultiplexes them" />
    <Advanced>
      <p>Because a connection is keyed by the full <b>4-tuple</b>, the famous "65,535 ports" limit is widely misread. A <i>server</i> isn't capped at 65k connections — it accepts on one fixed port, and each distinct <i>client</i> ip:port makes the tuple unique, so the real ceiling is memory and file descriptors. The 16-bit limit instead pinches the <i>client</i> side: a single host opening many connections to one server:port draws from a small pool of <b>ephemeral ports</b>.</p>
      <p>That pool is what gets exhausted in practice. TCP's <b>TIME_WAIT</b> state holds a closed connection's tuple for ~2×MSL to absorb stray late packets, so a client hammering one destination can run out of ephemeral ports long before any resource on the server does.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="One server machine runs many services and serves many clients, but a packet only carries addresses — something has to route it to the right program and the right conversation."
      idea="Address endpoints by ip:port (a socket) and identify each connection by the 4-tuple of both ends, so the OS can demultiplex every packet to its conversation."
      tradeoff="Ports are a finite 16-bit space and connection tables consume memory, so a busy server (or an attacker) can exhaust them."
      next="With a connection in place, the two ends finally speak — in HTTP."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.N7}>
    <p class="prose">Over that connection, the client and server speak <b>HTTP</b> — and it's just text. The client sends a <span class="hl">request</span> (a method like <code>GET</code>, a path, and headers); the server sends back a <span class="hl">response</span> (a <b>status code</b> like 200 or 404, headers, and a body). Each exchange stands alone — HTTP is <i>stateless</i>.</p>
    <Http client:visible />
    <Takeaway>HTTP is a stateless text protocol: method + path + headers up, status + headers + body down — the simple conversation the entire web is built on.</Takeaway>
    <Advanced>
      <p>Under the text protocol, two TCP optimizations can collide. <b>Nagle's algorithm</b> holds back a small write until the previous data is acked, to avoid flooding the wire with tiny packets; <b>delayed ACK</b> holds back an acknowledgement (~200 ms) hoping to piggyback it on a reply. Together they can <b>deadlock</b>: the sender waits for an ACK that the receiver is deliberately delaying — a notorious latency stall fixed by setting <code>TCP_NODELAY</code> for interactive traffic.</p>
      <p>HTTP/1.1 also forced requests down a connection one-at-a-time (or opened many connections), so <b>HTTP/2</b> multiplexes many concurrent requests as interleaved <b>streams</b> over a single connection. That removed HTTP-level head-of-line blocking but not TCP's — one lost packet still stalls every stream — which is the gap <b>HTTP/3</b> (QUIC over UDP) finally closes.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="A reliable byte stream is just bytes; applications need an agreed grammar for asking and answering — what do you want, and how did it go?"
      idea="Define a simple text protocol: a request with a method, path, and headers; a response with a status code, headers, and body — each request self-contained."
      tradeoff="Statelessness keeps it simple and scalable but pushes state elsewhere (cookies, tokens, sessions), and plain-text framing is why HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 added binary efficiency."
      next="Put DNS, the connection, encryption, and HTTP together and watch one click make the whole trip."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.N8}>
    <p class="prose">Type a URL and it all fires in order: <b>DNS</b> turns the name into an IP, <b>TCP</b> opens a connection (the SYN / SYN-ACK / ACK handshake), <b>TLS</b> negotiates keys and checks a certificate so the bytes are private, and finally <b>HTTP</b> carries your request — which descends every layer here, crosses the world, and climbs back up as a response.</p>
    <Takeaway>One click is this entire ladder, run twice — once down on the way out, once up on the way back.</Takeaway>
    <SeeAlso slug="crypto" note="how that connection is encrypted before any data flows (TLS)" />
    <Advanced>
      <p>Those round-trips stack up, so modern protocols collapse them. <b>TLS 1.3</b> needs just <b>one round-trip</b> (1-RTT) before encrypted data flows, down from two, and <b>QUIC</b> goes further by folding the transport and TLS handshakes together — often establishing a secure connection in a single round-trip, and resuming an earlier one in zero.</p>
      <p>That speed has a sharp edge: <b>0-RTT</b> data, sent on the first flight using a resumed key, can be <b>replayed</b> by an attacker who captures it. So 0-RTT is safe only for <i>idempotent</i> requests (a <code>GET</code> that just reads) and must never carry a state-changing action like a purchase or a transfer.</p>
    </Advanced>
    <Why
      problem="Each layer solves one problem in isolation, but a real request needs all of them composed in the right order, every time."
      idea="Stack them: names resolve, a connection opens, encryption wraps the channel, and the application protocol rides inside — each layer leaning on the promise of the one below."
      tradeoff="More layers means more round-trips and more places to fail; performance work (keep-alive, caching, QUIC) is mostly about collapsing this ladder."
      next="Zoom back out: this whole stack is one rung of the bigger climb from electrons to the cloud."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <Quiz slug="network" client:visible />
  <PrevNext slug="network" />
</Base>

<style>
  .back-link{color:var(--accent,var(--signal))}
</style>
